&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/rustyboxcars/4633235321/" title="Boycott BP"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4002/4633235321_4f7f322067_m.jpg" width="176" height="240" alt="Boycott BP" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;WASHINGTON – President Barack Obama moved aggressively to show his government is in charge of the Gulf oil spill on Thursday, calling the gushing leak an &amp;quot;unprecedented disaster&amp;quot; and blasting a &amp;quot;scandalously close relationship&amp;quot; between oil companies and regulators.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;quot;The American people should know that from the moment this disaster began, the federal government has been in charge of the response effort,&amp;quot; Obama told a news conference. He was responding to criticism that his administration had been slow to act and had left BP in charge of plugging the leak.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Obama said many critics failed to realize &amp;quot;this has been our highest priority.&amp;quot;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
He conceded that &amp;quot;people are going to be frustrated until it stops.&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;

