&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Returned to Johnson's Beach to see what High Time brought with it found the cleanup crews that started about 10:30am were gone. More Tar balls on the beach East of the Shelters. Debris washed in also had Black Oil.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/70524139@N00/"&gt;jaapberk&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/70524139@N00/4678853504/" title="Device to reduce oil flow Gulf of Mexico"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4034/4678853504_deb8efb3c2_m.jpg" width="180" height="240" alt="Device to reduce oil flow Gulf of Mexico" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Device to reduce oil flow Gulf of Mexico.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
To the Engineering Dept. Of BP.&lt;br /&gt;
This is a temporary solution.&lt;br /&gt;
(A)  leaking oil well.&lt;br /&gt;
Place a open pipe of 100m  length (L) en dia 6 feet over the leaking pipe.(1)&lt;br /&gt;
Weight of the pipe ca 3 T/m. Total weight 300 T.&lt;br /&gt;
Keep the pipe upright by wires to 3 or 4 selfpositioning workbarges .(2)&lt;br /&gt;
Fill the pipe with heavy liquid.&lt;br /&gt;
The pipe has a flexible collar at the bottom to avoid leakage of the heavy liquid. (3)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The weight of the liquid will reduce the oil flow.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Notes:&lt;br /&gt;
If according to your calculations the flow reduction is not enough, make the lenght of the pile 200 m.&lt;br /&gt;
The pipe has to be open at the top otherwise the collected oil will  lift the pipe.&lt;br /&gt;
A pipe of such dimensions can possibly be ready made found as they are used for mono tube breasting dolphins for oil terminals.&lt;br /&gt;
H.J.Berk M.Sc.Civil Engineering, University of Delft, Holland&lt;br /&gt;
berkbarto@hetnet.nl&lt;/p&gt;

