&lt;p&gt;Gulf of Mexio Oil Spill, June 15 2010: This is an enhanced satellite image of the oil spill and clean up effort in the Gulf of Mexico. This image leverages the different sensor bands of our WorldView-2 satellite to highlight the oil and dispersant. (credit:DigitalGlobe)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/radiobiz/"&gt;Brian Hart&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/radiobiz/4711823117/" title="Oil Boom blocks Roberts Bayou"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4056/4711823117_861e8ef0db_m.jpg" width="159" height="240" alt="Oil Boom blocks Roberts Bayou" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3 layers of boom currently block Roberts Bayou.  The orange line is blocking boom designed to keep oil from entering the bayou.  The white string is absorbing boom designed to absorb any oil that overuns the orange line.  And the yellow line is another blocking sting of boom.  None of this will stop oil more than a few inches under the surface.&lt;/p&gt;

