&lt;p&gt;Oil boom deployed across Roberts Bayou in Josephine, Alabama in response to the BP Deepwater Horizon oil spill.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/radiobiz/"&gt;Brian Hart&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/radiobiz/4724257966/" title="Blocking Perdido Pass"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1002/4724257966_367b5809e0_m.jpg" width="240" height="161" alt="Blocking Perdido Pass" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Crews work to block Perdido Pass in response to the BP Deepwater Horizon Oil Spill.  Floating boom has proven ineffective against the tides and wave action so the current plan is to use a rigid boom system.  These metal pilings are anchored to the sea floor.  3 foot diameter steel pipes are filled with Styrofoam and tied to the pilings.&lt;/p&gt;

