&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/radiobiz/4728481519/" title="diving pelicans"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1236/4728481519_1b9182e1ce_m.jpg" width="240" height="161" alt="diving pelicans" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2 pelicans diving for fish as cleanup continues in Mobile Bay.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/radiobiz/"&gt;Brian Hart&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/radiobiz/4728482245/" title="HMMV's"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1111/4728482245_22eb254b00_m.jpg" width="240" height="161" alt="HMMV's" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Alabama Governor Bob Riley has called up the Alabama National Guard to aid in oil response.  Today they were working on barriers protecting the sensitive wetlands and beach habits in the bird sanctuary at Fort Morgan.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/radiobiz/"&gt;Brian Hart&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/radiobiz/4728586021/" title="Oil in the clouds?"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1181/4728586021_924fd7cc8d_m.jpg" width="240" height="160" alt="Oil in the clouds?" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Videos of what appears to be oily water raining down in Florida and Louisiana are starting to show up on sites like youtube.  I heard an interesting theory today.  A group of men were talking and they think that the red or brown tinted clouds are the ones holding oil.  You don't really see them until you look through polarized lenses but then they stand out - as you can see in this photo.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Now I have no idea if that theory holds water, so to speak, since I don't know much about cloud formation or how and when oil evaporates but I found it to be an interesting discussion none the less.  Thoughts?&lt;/p&gt;

