&lt;p&gt;This trailer is full of bags containing tar balls and other oil spill related debris.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/radiobiz/"&gt;Brian Hart&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/radiobiz/4732983381/" title="Southern innovation"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1114/4732983381_3603ec5d95_m.jpg" width="161" height="240" alt="Southern innovation" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This trailer has been outfitted with benches and a canopy made from PVC pipe and a tarp to protect oil response workers from the brutal coastal sun.  Front end loaders drag these trailers up and down the beach ferrying workers back and forth to clean up sites.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/radiobiz/"&gt;Brian Hart&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/radiobiz/4733623814/" title="Red Flags Again"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1312/4733623814_8d76f07940_m.jpg" width="161" height="240" alt="Red Flags Again" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The red flags are once again flying across many areas of the beach in Florida and Alabama.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Normally one would see these flags due to an approaching hurricane etc.  Officials use them now to warn the public about oil contaminated water.  The beaches are still open but beachgoers are told to stay above the high tide line.&lt;/p&gt;

