&lt;p&gt;This was one sign on the beach that we saw.   It was strange because everything on the internet and local news says that the waters are perfectly safe.  Maybe not.  There were many of us in the water until my husband noticed this one little sign...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/znude/"&gt;Bayou Campers&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/znude/4794772179/" title="Tar Ball from BP disaster on Ship Island"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4140/4794772179_4ac6a3c8cb_m.jpg" width="240" height="127" alt="Tar Ball from BP disaster on Ship Island" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Today I found that many areas of Ship Island are covered with crude oil from the BP disaster. It's very heart breaking.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Currently (the middle of July) there are large areas of Ship Island that are covered in a small patchwork of tar balls like this one. They are thick but not so thick that you can't walk through them without stepping on them. In some areas of about a thousand square feet at a time you have to go around them to avoid them. I saw at least two areas towards the very east end of West Ship where there were warning signs encouraging people to keep out. The majority of the beach both bay side and Gulf side are free of tar from the boat dock to the end of the dunes. On the Gulf side the water was beautiful, no oil sheen in sight anywhere. On the bay side the water was kind murky but this is not unusual. There was an area on the bay side at the east end where there was a good bit of oil which was captured by boom.&lt;br /&gt;
Currently the island is still a great place to spend the day. I believe wildlife is being effected even now. There was a lot of fish all around the island and I saw at least a half dozen sharks about five or six feet long having a buffet. The birds seemed really agitated. I have a bad feeling about what's to come out here. Enjoy it while you can.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/znude/"&gt;Bayou Campers&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/znude/4795404960/" title="Distressed Bird"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4082/4795404960_0648c486f5_m.jpg" width="240" height="128" alt="Distressed Bird" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have a feeling this is a small sign of what's to come out on beautiful Ship Island. I have a feeling this chick was fed some food tainted by the oil spill. The chick was still alive and hiding near a piece of old scrap rope. He could have been just a stray that got out of the nest and sometimes when they are sick I think mom or dad throws them out. But it almost looks like patches of oil on his feathers. I'm no expert so I can't say.&lt;/p&gt;

